ke","Haemolysis","Gilbert syndrome","Crigler-Najjar syndrome","Choledocholithiasis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe metabolism of bilirubin involves several steps. \u003Cstrong\u003EHaemolysis\u003C/strong\u003E causes increased production of unconjugated bilirubin. \u003Cstrong\u003EReduced hepatocyte uptake\u003C/strong\u003E prevents unconjugated bilirubin from entering liver cells. \u003Cstrong\u003EGilbert syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003ECrigler-Najjar syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E are genetic conditions that impair bilirubin conjugation, leading to unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBiliary obstruction from \u003Cstrong\u003Echoledocholithiasis\u003C/strong\u003E prevents the excretion of already conjugated bilirubin into the bile canaliculi. This causes backup of conjugated bilirubin into the blood, resulting in conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia. This pattern is also seen in other causes of cholestasis, such as carcinoma of the head of the pancreas.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia occurs when there is impaired excretion of conjugated bilirubin into bile canaliculi.","Bilirubin is conjugated with glucuronic acid in hepatocytes to make it water soluble for excretion.","Cholestasis leads to accumulation of conjugated bilirubin in blood."],"references":["Joseph A, Samant H. Jaundice. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31334972.","amada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Gasmi B, Kleiner DE. Liver Histology: Diagnostic and Prognostic Features. Clin Liver Dis. 2020 Feb;24(1):61-74. doi: 10.1016/j.cld.2019.09.004. Epub 2019 Oct 31. PMID: 31753251; PMCID: PMC6986808"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51335"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15313"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51335"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T12:34:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T12:34:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8004"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65890"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"